00:08:36,220 --> 00:08:39,462
And each one of those has unique challenges and advantages and disadvantages.

125
00:08:40,082 --> 00:08:41,463
And there's probably other methods out there.

126
00:08:41,503 --> 00:08:43,365
These are just the four that I was really familiar with.

127
00:08:45,274 --> 00:08:48,217
What we chose to do was use a dynapack for our cars.

128
00:08:49,058 --> 00:08:53,122
We took our tyres to a racetrack, we did our trucks out on the open road, and then boats

129
00:08:53,202 --> 00:08:55,564
we recorded both in water and on dry land.

130
00:08:56,045 --> 00:08:57,806
And I'll go into more detail on that in a moment.

131
00:09:00,247 --> 00:09:02,128
If you're not familiar, what's a dyno?

132
00:09:02,148 --> 00:09:06,330
A dyno is basically a treadmill that lets you put your car on it and drive the car at

133
00:09:06,390 --> 00:09:07,951
any speed you want while it's not moving.

134
00:09:08,371 --> 00:09:13,154
It's something that allows a mechanic to tune the car, measure the performance of the car

135
00:09:13,194 --> 00:09:17,736
and basically change the performance of a car at all different speeds while it's stationary.

136
00:09:19,897 --> 00:09:20,858
So why choose a dyno?

137
00:09:20,998 --> 00:09:26,561
It would be so much more fun to get out on a racetrack and thrash around in these cars.

138
00:09:26,681 --> 00:09:27,481
Why do this method?

139
00:09:28,804 --> 00:09:30,806
For us, it was a few things.

140
00:09:30,866 --> 00:09:32,047
It was really a matter of safety.

141
00:09:32,367 --> 00:09:35,330
We're dealing with old cars that are 45 to 75 years old.

142
00:09:36,050 --> 00:09:37,251
I don't know how reliable they are.

143
00:09:37,371 --> 00:09:38,412
I don't know if the brakes work.

144
00:09:38,452 --> 00:09:39,513
I don't know if the steering works.

145
00:09:39,773 --> 00:09:43,436
I don't really want to put my team members in these cars and send them off at high speed

146
00:09:43,476 --> 00:09:44,117
down a racetrack.

147
00:09:46,205 --> 00:09:48,545
But it also provides a really controlled recording environment.

148
00:09:49,566 --> 00:09:53,747
We minimize the risk of damage to these cars and we have this hands-off miking approach.

149
00:09:54,787 --> 00:09:57,727
When I started speaking to some of the vehicle owners, they got really concerned.

150
00:09:57,747 --> 00:10:01,868
They imagined us driving around a racetrack with all sorts of stuff clamped and taped

151
00:10:01,888 --> 00:10:02,809
to the side of their cars.

152
00:10:02,989 --> 00:10:07,630
And these are old show cars with beautiful paint jobs and they take them to displays

153
00:10:07,670 --> 00:10:08,970
but they don't really want to push them that hard.

154
00:10:09,691 --> 00:10:14,659
So when we started suggesting this as a method to record, we earned their trust much more

155
00:10:14,699 --> 00:10:18,144
easily and they were willing to work with us because it was a much more hands-off approach,

156
00:10:18,204 --> 00:10:19,386
much more controlled environment.

157
00:10:22,055 --> 00:10:24,956
The downside of recording with a dyno is that it can be kind of too clinical.

158
00:10:25,116 --> 00:10:27,337
Sometimes you lose some of that great character of an engine.

159
00:10:28,137 --> 00:10:29,738
And you also have a lot of overheating risks.

160
00:10:30,238 --> 00:10:33,599
When you're in a controlled room like that, you have to put really large fans in the front

161
00:10:33,619 --> 00:10:37,661
of the engine to bring airflow in and exhaust fans at the back to pull the exhaust out.

162
00:10:38,361 --> 00:10:41,743
And we don't want that for recording, so we would record with the fans off, which meant

163
00:10:41,783 --> 00:10:43,883
we had to be really, really careful to not overheat the cars.

164
00:10:46,244 --> 00:10:49,365
Here's a picture of the dyno we used with a 1940s Plymouth.

165
00:10:52,732 --> 00:10:55,293
So there's two different types of dynos that at least I'm aware of.

166
00:10:55,913 --> 00:11:00,395
There's a traditional roller dyno which is really quick, it's really easy, you just drive

167
00:11:00,415 --> 00:11:04,056
the car straight on, it works with almost any type of car and it's really common, easy

168
00:11:04,096 --> 00:11:04,436
to find.

169
00:11:05,137 --> 00:11:08,878
The downside is that the rollers themselves produce so much noise that it kind of makes

170
00:11:08,918 --> 00:11:10,039
it impractical for recording.

171
00:11:10,939 --> 00:11:14,480
There's also a slight safety risk in that there's a lot of inertia involved in the car

172
00:11:14,540 --> 00:11:17,081
and it can break and launch forward into the wall.

173
00:11:18,462 --> 00:11:21,683
But really the biggest downside for us is the noise, it just ruins the recording.

174
00:11:23,084 --> 00:11:28,008
So if you use a DynaPak, which is a brand developed in New Zealand, it's basically a hydraulic

175
00:11:28,048 --> 00:11:28,308
brake.

176
00:11:28,649 --> 00:11:32,772
You take the wheels off the car, you bolt this machine directly onto the wheels, and

177
00:11:32,812 --> 00:11:36,715
it's a computer-controlled brake that dials up the resistance and the load on the engine.

178
00:11:37,736 --> 00:11:39,678
The big bonus is that it's practically silent.

179
00:11:39,758 --> 00:11:40,659
It makes no noise at all.

180
00:11:41,279 --> 00:11:44,682
It's really accurate, because we're working with old cars where the gauges probably aren't

181
00:11:44,722 --> 00:11:45,403
really that accurate.

182
00:11:46,243 --> 00:11:46,924
And it's really safe.

183
00:11:46,984 --> 00:11:47,724
There's no inertia.

184
00:11:47,765 --> 00:11:50,126
There's no chance the car can brake and launch forward.

185
00:11:51,799 --> 00:11:56,103
The downside to it is that they're really rare, they're hard to find, and you usually

186
00:11:56,143 --> 00:11:58,726
have to work with a high performance workshop that's really expensive.

187
00:11:59,627 --> 00:12:03,651
It takes a lot longer to put the car on and off the dyno, you have to basically jack it

188
00:12:03,691 --> 00:12:06,013
up and take the wheels off, so there's more time invested.

189
00:12:07,398 --> 00:12:10,840
And one of the other downsides is that there's certain cars it just won't work with.

190
00:12:11,001 --> 00:12:15,404
You know, if you have side exhaust pipes or really wide fenders or non-standard wheel

191
00:12:15,424 --> 00:12:18,126
types, chances are you can't put the car on the dyno.

