00:14:28,328 --> 00:14:30,850
And it's a really inefficient cooling type car.

231
00:14:30,890 --> 00:14:34,152
So this car, we could record for 12 seconds and then it would overheat and we'd have to

232
00:14:34,192 --> 00:14:34,912
stop for 10 minutes.

233
00:14:34,992 --> 00:14:37,394
And then we could record for 12 seconds and then stop for 10 minutes.

234
00:14:38,034 --> 00:14:39,455
But it sounded so amazing it was worth it.

235
00:14:40,616 --> 00:14:44,638
At the other end of the spectrum we had a European car whose name I'm not allowed to

236
00:14:44,658 --> 00:14:44,798
mention.

237
00:14:45,573 --> 00:14:48,455
mention, but they're Italian and they like red.

238
00:14:49,956 --> 00:14:53,198
And the owner of that car basically said, you know, you

239
00:14:53,218 --> 00:14:54,819
can do whatever this thing lets you do.

240
00:14:54,939 --> 00:14:56,780
Push it to 8,500 RPM if you want.

241
00:14:57,420 --> 00:14:57,780
And we did.

242
00:14:58,000 --> 00:14:58,821
And it sounded fantastic.

243
00:15:00,063 --> 00:15:02,565
One of the things we learned, that regular cars just sound kind of boring.

244
00:15:03,565 --> 00:15:07,309
We had this idea of not everyone in the city owns a hot rod, so we have to have this mixture

245
00:15:07,349 --> 00:15:08,950
of regular and high performance cars.

246
00:15:09,631 --> 00:15:12,193
And the regular cars just sounded more boring than we thought they would.

247
00:15:12,673 --> 00:15:16,917
So I think for future, we will always go with slightly modified and heavily modified cars.

248
00:15:18,138 --> 00:15:20,960
And then the really obvious one was that anything with a rear engine was going to be really

249
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:23,282
difficult to get a separation of engine and exhaust.

250
00:15:25,187 --> 00:15:28,370
So specifically some of the things that went wrong, we had some cars with starter motor

251
00:15:28,410 --> 00:15:33,773
issues, one car had a carburettor issue, two overheated, we had some cars that didn't show

252
00:15:33,853 --> 00:15:38,556
up on brief, they had different wheels and different exhaust pipes, we even had some

253
00:15:38,616 --> 00:15:42,159
car owners who they had these really beautiful show cars and they wouldn't drive them if

254
00:15:42,219 --> 00:15:43,940
it was a wet road the day after raining.

255
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:48,423
So the key there is really to have backups planned before your recording session.

256
00:15:50,304 --> 00:15:53,226
So now we know what we're going to record, where we're going to record and how we're

257
00:15:53,246 --> 00:15:53,727
going to record.

258
00:15:54,383 --> 00:15:57,685
But now we get down to the meat and potatoes of what we're actually going to capture.

259
00:15:58,565 --> 00:16:02,767
We decided to do engine start, stop, false start, idle, rev blips.

260
00:16:03,287 --> 00:16:07,889
We do ramp runs, which is basically getting the car from idle all the way to maximum RPM,

261
00:16:08,029 --> 00:16:09,470
and we would do that fast and slow.

262
00:16:09,890 --> 00:16:12,671
And that was mainly as a reference, so we could hear what the car should sound like

263
00:16:13,291 --> 00:16:15,172
as it's accelerating and decelerating.

264
00:16:16,452 --> 00:16:20,554
We decided to record loops of about six seconds, which we didn't need that much, but it was

265
00:16:20,594 --> 00:16:21,594
just enough for us to work with.

266
00:16:22,462 --> 00:16:24,363
And we would put a really high load on the engine,

267
00:16:24,423 --> 00:16:27,284
and we'd do a really fine level of loops,

268
00:16:27,424 --> 00:16:29,724
you know, 200 RPM increments all the way up to 2,000,

269
00:16:30,024 --> 00:16:32,745
and then 500 RPM increments up to redline.

270
00:16:33,525 --> 00:16:35,746
And then we'd repeat that whole process under a low load.

271
00:16:36,866 --> 00:16:38,266
Our goal was to get three perspectives.

272
00:16:38,466 --> 00:16:40,727
We wanted the engine, the exhaust, and the interior.

273
00:16:41,587 --> 00:16:43,348
And then afterwards, when one car was finished,

274
00:16:43,368 --> 00:16:45,548
we'd take it to another location and do a Foley session

275
00:16:45,588 --> 00:16:47,049
of everything that opened and closed

276
00:16:47,109 --> 00:16:47,989
and clinked and clunked

277
00:16:48,969 --> 00:16:50,230
while we started preparing the next car.

278
00:16:52,315 --> 00:16:55,996
The gear we used, I won't run through this in high detail, but basically it was an 8

279
00:16:56,136 --> 00:16:57,376
channel sound devices unit.

280
00:16:58,817 --> 00:17:03,138
If I could only choose one microphone for vehicle recordings it would be the DPA 4060s.

281
00:17:04,039 --> 00:17:08,880
They were reliable in every single situation and really versatile and if I could choose

282
00:17:08,960 --> 00:17:09,800
one mic that would be it.

283
00:17:13,481 --> 00:17:17,164
I guess the other one to note is the AKG D112s, which are really designed for kick drums,

284
00:17:17,585 --> 00:17:20,947
but we used them on exhausts to get that really low rumble of the exhaust.

285
00:17:21,648 --> 00:17:24,230
And then over time as we did these sessions, you know, we expanded our kit.

286
00:17:24,270 --> 00:17:27,233
We were recording directly into Pro Tools through an interface at one point.

287
00:17:27,933 --> 00:17:31,496
We added a Zoom F8 so that we could slave the two together and get 16 channels.

288
00:17:31,937 --> 00:17:33,598
So over time we kind of expanded our kit.

289
00:17:35,853 --> 00:17:38,775
Just really simple extra common sense stuff to bring to a recording session.

290
00:17:39,095 --> 00:17:43,697
Bring cameras, bring first aid kits, spare cables and batteries of every kind.

291
00:17:44,258 --> 00:17:46,399
And probably the most important thing to note there is sandbags.

292
00:17:47,060 --> 00:17:52,783
The last thing I want to do is hang a boom over a $150,000 Porsche and have the mic stand

293
00:17:52,823 --> 00:17:53,804
fall over and dent the car.

294
00:17:54,224 --> 00:17:57,386
So it's really important to get some really cheap sandbags and weight everything down.

295
00:18:00,292 --> 00:18:02,234
Some really common sense tips when you're recording cars.

296
00:18:02,534 --> 00:18:04,095
Confirm everything the day before.

297
00:18:04,395 --> 00:18:06,996
It's not as important to them to show up to your session as it is to you.

298
00:18:08,197 --> 00:18:10,398
Plan plenty of backup cars in case if you can.

299
00:18:11,018 --> 00:18:11,579
Be flexible.

300
00:18:11,619 --> 00:18:12,980
Some of these cars don't do what you want.

301
00:18:13,140 --> 00:18:15,681
So it's really important to adjust your priorities.

302
00:18:15,801 --> 00:18:19,243
And if a car is overheating, you may have to kind of decide what are the most important

303
00:18:19,283 --> 00:18:23,085
things that I need to record now and kind of change your plan around a little bit.

304
00:18:24,628 --> 00:18:26,409
And then just use whatever method is the easiest.

305
00:18:26,929 --> 00:18:30,230
It's really impractical to be typing into an iPad when you're moving on a boat at 90

306
00:18:30,510 --> 00:18:31,011
miles an hour.

307
00:18:31,131 --> 00:18:36,273
So use pen and paper, use laminated sheets, use whatever is really simple and just easy.

308
00:18:37,253 --> 00:18:41,695
And then the biggest takeaway here is investigate what your legal issues and permits and insurance

309
00:18:41,735 --> 00:18:43,236
needs are really far in advance.

310
00:18:44,677 --> 00:18:48,418
For our Tire session, which I'll show you in a moment, we started working with our legal

311
00:18:48,458 --> 00:18:50,519
team maybe three months before the recording session.

312
00:18:51,079 --> 00:18:53,100
And their rules were really simple.

313
00:18:53,460 --> 00:18:55,460
Don't break the law, be safe and responsible.

314
00:18:56,080 --> 00:18:58,061
And everything from that they were willing to support us with.

315
00:18:58,321 --> 00:19:01,262
But sometimes that can take a really long time to prepare.

316
00:19:01,482 --> 00:19:04,443
We had to prepare nearly three months in advance for that recording session.

317
00:19:07,563 --> 00:19:08,503
So, where to place the mic?

318
00:19:08,723 --> 00:19:11,444
Well, this is as open a question as any.

319
00:19:12,085 --> 00:19:12,865
It's all down to choice.

320
00:19:13,525 --> 00:19:17,827
For an eight mic setup, we chose to put three in the engine bay, four on the exhaust for

321
00:19:17,867 --> 00:19:19,888
a dual exhaust system, and one on the interior.

322
00:19:20,869 --> 00:19:23,650
Over time, we expanded to a 16 mic setup.

323
00:19:24,250 --> 00:19:26,491
And that wasn't really because we needed more coverage of the car.

324
00:19:26,612 --> 00:19:29,253
It was just because we were getting different tonalities from different mics.

325
00:19:29,513 --> 00:19:32,914
And on some of those really expensive rare cars, we just wanted to have backup channels

326
00:19:32,974 --> 00:19:33,195
as well.

327
00:19:34,988 --> 00:19:39,390
But specifically we would put the DPA labs inside the engine bay and usually we would

328
00:19:39,430 --> 00:19:43,431
put one close to the intake to get that kind of sucking air sound and then we'd look for

329
00:19:43,491 --> 00:19:45,632
something else that was unique and different inside the engine.

330
00:19:45,912 --> 00:19:49,894
And sometimes that was down at the back firewall, sometimes it was underneath the engine near

331
00:19:49,914 --> 00:19:51,114
the exhaust manifold.

332
00:19:52,535 --> 00:19:55,436
It was basically just looking for something that was different and unique about that engine.

333
00:19:56,536 --> 00:19:59,457
And then we would have one mic a few feet back from the engine to just get an overall

334
00:19:59,477 --> 00:19:59,738
picture.

335
00:20:00,667 --> 00:20:05,350
And we would put two shotguns at the back of the exhaust and then the two AKG D112s

336
00:20:05,370 --> 00:20:06,731
to get the low rumble of the exhaust.

337
00:20:07,371 --> 00:20:10,533
And then usually just one mic on the interior down where the passenger's feet would go.

338
00:20:13,575 --> 00:20:15,956
And I'll show you a video of the cars towards the end.

339
00:20:17,137 --> 00:20:19,158
When it comes to trucks, it's an entirely different beast.

340
00:20:19,959 --> 00:20:22,661
The challenges we had was being able to record them in isolation.

341
00:20:22,821 --> 00:20:24,382
We couldn't find a dyno for trucks.

342
00:20:25,483 --> 00:20:27,264
So we ended up recording them out on the open road.

343
00:20:28,035 --> 00:20:30,515
We did one day per truck just by myself.

344
00:20:31,576 --> 00:20:35,037
And the most important thing is a highly skilled driver is more important than the truck itself.

345
00:20:36,497 --> 00:20:37,518
And I'll get into that in a moment.

346
00:20:39,338 --> 00:20:41,699
Trucks are really hot engines.

347
00:20:41,759 --> 00:20:45,140
And I was really worried about these really thin mic cables just melting in five minutes.

348
00:20:45,640 --> 00:20:49,321
So what I ended up doing was going to a hardware store and buying dishwasher hose.

349
00:20:49,541 --> 00:20:50,241
It was really cheap.

350
00:20:50,761 --> 00:20:54,663
It was a way to run all the mic cables through and insulate them and we were able to do these

351
00:20:54,683 --> 00:20:55,923
sessions without damaging anything.

352
00:20:57,870 --> 00:21:02,252
The truck itself is a big clunky machine, so you try and use the body of the truck to

353
00:21:02,292 --> 00:21:04,613
build natural windbreaks, and I'll show you a picture of that.

354
00:21:05,953 --> 00:21:09,955
Here you can see kind of towards the back of the truck, we used the frame to position

355
00:21:09,995 --> 00:21:13,696
our mics and we wrapped them in foam and tried to use the cabin of the truck to protect us

356
00:21:13,716 --> 00:21:14,157
from the wind.

357
00:21:15,757 --> 00:21:17,758
The real challenge was recording steady states.

358
00:21:19,357 --> 00:21:23,200
So, what we did, we had this really skilled driver who went all up through the hills of

359
00:21:23,240 --> 00:21:27,583
Marin Headlands and he knew exactly which road to be on to be the right gradient of

360
00:21:27,623 --> 00:21:30,945
hill with the right amount of load on the engine and the right gear so that he could

361
00:21:31,005 --> 00:21:34,767
hold the truck really steady under load and let us get a usable loop.

362
00:21:35,688 --> 00:21:38,630
And then we did the whole process again by adding weight to the truck and he added the

363
00:21:38,650 --> 00:21:38,930
trailer.

364
00:21:40,401 --> 00:21:44,084
With a truck, the one characteristic that I really wanted to capture is called the jake

365
00:21:44,104 --> 00:21:44,324
brake.

366
00:21:45,705 --> 00:21:46,866
It's an exhaust system.

367
00:21:46,886 --> 00:21:50,008
I don't know if you hear trucks go downhill and they kind of make that ba-ba-ba-ba-ba

368
00:21:50,168 --> 00:21:51,629
sound that some people don't like.

369
00:21:53,111 --> 00:21:57,574
That's a valve that uses the truck's pressure to help slow it down.

370
00:21:57,634 --> 00:22:00,136
And that was something we really wanted to capture and use in the game.

371
00:22:02,058 --> 00:22:05,941
I'd like to play you just a really quick sample of how our final results of our trucks ended

372
00:22:05,981 --> 00:22:06,461
up in the game.

373
00:22:06,521 --> 00:22:08,583
This runs for about a minute, a minute and a half.

374
00:22:22,516 --> 00:22:23,839
Thanks for watching.

375
00:23:28,555 --> 00:23:31,257
So, when it came to boats, again, that was an entirely different process.

376
00:23:35,169 --> 00:23:38,332
We did a three day recording session to capture seven different boat engines.

377
00:23:38,812 --> 00:23:42,575
And again, early on in the process, we didn't know exactly what the final art models would

378
00:23:42,615 --> 00:23:47,879
be, but we knew we had to provide small fishing boats, medium boats, some sort of high speed

379
00:23:47,959 --> 00:23:53,724
drug smuggling boat, some sort of large police patrol or coast guard boat, and then the kind

380
00:23:53,764 --> 00:23:55,425
of bayou swamp fan boat.

381
00:23:58,507 --> 00:24:02,450
What we found was that the really small, less than 10 horsepower engines, it's really easy

382
00:24:02,490 --> 00:24:03,311
to record them in a tank.

383
00:24:04,647 --> 00:24:08,692
We found that being out on the water wasn't so difficult for us to maintain steady RPM

384
00:24:08,732 --> 00:24:09,052
states.

385
00:24:09,573 --> 00:24:13,998
If you can go out on a smooth, calm, nice weather day, that really helps compared to

386
00:24:14,038 --> 00:24:14,559
choppy weather.

387
00:24:15,712 --> 00:24:20,114
And one thing we learned was that the exhaust of most boats is submerged under the water,

388
00:24:20,154 --> 00:24:24,276
so it really offers you nothing to record other than that slight kind of glug, glug,

389
00:24:24,296 --> 00:24:25,436
glug sound when you're at idle.

390
00:24:26,236 --> 00:24:29,718
So what we decided to do was record a second pass of each boat on dry land.

391
00:24:30,238 --> 00:24:33,739
And what you can do is connect, you know, the boats need water for cooling, but you

392
00:24:33,779 --> 00:24:37,641
can connect the hose to the engine and then you can record a second pass to get that exhaust

393
00:24:37,681 --> 00:24:40,222
and get that really aggressive bite that we wanted from the boats.

394
00:24:40,482 --> 00:24:41,942
And then we blended those recordings together.

395
00:24:45,811 --> 00:24:49,853
What we decided to do was take the engine covers off, put the DPAs under the engine.

396
00:24:50,713 --> 00:24:55,555
We knew that the blimps and shotgun mics were going to, at some level, they were going to

397
00:24:55,595 --> 00:24:58,417
work for low speeds and then at higher speeds they were going to become useless.

398
00:24:59,057 --> 00:25:03,039
So having those DPA mics under the engine covers, we had a natural windbreak and it

399
00:25:03,119 --> 00:25:07,341
didn't matter what speed, what RPM we were at, we knew we would get some clean, reliable

400
00:25:07,381 --> 00:25:08,181
recordings from them.

401
00:25:12,643 --> 00:25:14,104
I had this growing concern that...

402
00:25:15,312 --> 00:25:17,472
You know, salt water and microphones don't mix.

403
00:25:18,053 --> 00:25:21,374
And we could have very easily just destroyed all our gear in one day.

404
00:25:21,614 --> 00:25:23,394
And we knew everything was going to get really wet.

405
00:25:23,975 --> 00:25:27,716
So I decided to go to one of those fabric stores where they sell sewing material.

406
00:25:27,756 --> 00:25:30,857
And I said, do you guys sell anything, any kind of waterproof fabric that I could buy?

407
00:25:30,877 --> 00:25:32,878
And they said, yeah, sure.

408
00:25:32,958 --> 00:25:34,218
This is our baby diaper section.

409
00:25:34,618 --> 00:25:37,119
You can have camouflage or you can have this.

410
00:25:38,260 --> 00:25:39,720
And I thought about it for a while.

411
00:25:40,529 --> 00:25:44,793
We went with the camouflage, but we basically bought this fabric, wrapped up the mics, sprayed

412
00:25:44,813 --> 00:25:49,337
them with that Scotchgard stuff that's great for your shoes, and made sure we kind of pointed

413
00:25:49,357 --> 00:25:50,578
the back of the mic into the wind.

414
00:25:50,698 --> 00:25:54,421
And you know, these things got soaked every single day, but we were able to protect, you

415
00:25:54,641 --> 00:25:58,824
know, for maybe $30 worth of extra materials, we were able to protect all our gear and not

416
00:25:58,844 --> 00:25:59,385
break anything.

417
00:26:00,166 --> 00:26:01,146
So, that was really worthwhile.

418
00:26:01,327 --> 00:26:05,630
And then we used a contact mic on the hull of the boat to get all the thumps and bumps.

419
00:26:07,329 --> 00:26:11,312
What I would like to show you is a quick video of the recording session and one more quick

420
00:26:11,352 --> 00:26:13,074
video of how those boats ended up in game.

421
00:26:39,244 --> 00:26:40,385
Thanks for watching!

422
00:28:17,923 --> 00:28:18,904
That was a really, really fun day.

423
00:28:18,925 --> 00:28:22,829
Here's a little quick sample of how some of those sounds got used in game.

424
00:28:24,290 --> 00:28:27,874
What you'll hear is more of the water spray, more of the thumps and bumps and some of the

425
00:28:27,894 --> 00:28:28,695
different things we did.

426
00:28:28,875 --> 00:28:32,479
On the fan boat, you'll hear that we added vibrations for rudder control and all that

427
00:28:32,499 --> 00:28:32,939
kind of stuff.

428
00:28:33,720 --> 00:28:36,663
So here's an example of how our final boat audio ended up in game.

429
00:29:31,698 --> 00:29:32,198
Don't forget to subscribe!

430
00:30:23,096 --> 00:30:27,859
Some of the additional pieces that we added to the engine, our designers wanted to add

431
00:30:27,899 --> 00:30:33,083
forced induction, superchargers and turbochargers, and the difficult part about recording a supercharger

432
00:30:33,123 --> 00:30:35,965
is that the engine that is underneath it, of course, is going to be loud.

433
00:30:36,705 --> 00:30:42,209
So we contacted a factory that makes superchargers down in Southern California, and by total

434
00:30:42,249 --> 00:30:46,652
luck, they have a completely soundproof room in their factory where they spool these up

435
00:30:46,712 --> 00:30:50,315
on electric motors and test them and make sure that they're working properly before

436
00:30:50,355 --> 00:30:51,976
they package them off to their customers.

437
00:30:52,821 --> 00:30:55,023
I couldn't have been more lucky with the conditions.

438
00:30:55,203 --> 00:30:57,565
And they agreed to let us in there, so we recorded that way.

439
00:30:58,406 --> 00:30:59,687
The turbo was a little more difficult.

440
00:30:59,727 --> 00:31:03,770
We couldn't find a similar situation, so it became a combination of real turbos,

441
00:31:04,911 --> 00:31:06,693
sound design and foley.

442
00:31:07,033 --> 00:31:10,917
We used ball-bearing keychains, compressed air, hospital defibrillators

443
00:31:10,977 --> 00:31:12,858
and all sorts of different things to make our turbo sounds.

444
00:31:14,729 --> 00:31:19,810
With the police sirens, we also had a real hard time finding a car with a 1960s siren.

445
00:31:19,950 --> 00:31:24,871
It was early 60s where they started experimenting with electronic sirens and went away from

446
00:31:24,911 --> 00:31:27,051
the old rotating impeller type sirens.

447
00:31:27,812 --> 00:31:31,952
So we ended up going to eBay and just buying a siren and that's how we managed to capture

448
00:31:31,992 --> 00:31:32,133
that.

449
00:31:32,573 --> 00:31:37,274
We also found that a lot of the sounds from a 1960s police siren is due to the police

450
00:31:37,314 --> 00:31:41,835
officers messing with the buttons and kind of moving the siren halfway between two different

451
00:31:41,855 --> 00:31:43,775
positions and kind of messing with it that way.

452
00:31:43,835 --> 00:31:44,155
So that's...

453
00:31:45,216 --> 00:31:47,076
That was something we really wanted to capture and recreate.

454
00:31:49,537 --> 00:31:53,038
Brings me to tires. This was also one of the most fun parts of the whole project for us.

455
00:31:54,878 --> 00:31:58,699
Our goals were to capture a clean set of tire sounds in isolation from an engine.

456
00:31:59,559 --> 00:32:02,320
We wanted to capture multiple different surfaces, including a wet road,

457
00:32:02,700 --> 00:32:05,101
